Introducing Roving Tabindex

Remember when we looked at the radio button group in the Component Sandbox that allowed us to hit Tab to reach the group, use Arrow keys to change the selection, then hit Tab again to move on?

That pattern is called roving tabindex.

The goal of this section of the workshop is to implement this pattern with the custom date picker component found on the Listing detail template of the CampSpots app.

Interacting with the Current Date Picker

Back in the CampSpots app, head over to one of the Listing detail pages. If you’re running the development server locally, the listing for Cranberry Lake will work just fine.

Tabbing over to the date picker (with help from the skip link if you have it implemented!), notice how every day in the calendar has to be tabbed through in order to move beyond it.

If this was implemented as a scrolling calendar that moved to the next month, a keyboard user would never get past it.

The Current Date Picker Implementation

Before diving right in to implementing roving tabindex for the date picker, let’s look at its current implementation.

The component’s source code is located at components/date-picker/date-picker.js if you want to follow along.

Date Functionality with Day.js

At the top of the file we import the Day.js package, which is an awesome package for working with dates. This way we don’t have to manually keep track of how many days are in a certain month or what day of the week they fall on.

The DatePicker component includes logic for navigating months and blocking dates from being booked if they are unavailable.

Check out components/date-picker/utils.js to see more Day.js code in action.

Current DatePicker Markup

Inside the return() at line 114 is where the actual markup of the DatePicker component starts.

There are separate controls for navigating to the previous and next months. They use buttons and therefore are reachable and operable by the keyboard.

What we’re really interested in fixing here is at line 171 where the the date grid is created by mapping over the days in the week to create buttons.

Here are the important bits of the markup for each button that gets created:

<button
	aria-disabled={day.isBooked ? 'true' : 'false'}
	aria-label={} // either the number or "already booked" or "selected"
	aria-selected={isDaySelected(day) ? 'true' : 'false'}
	className={...}
	onClick={() => selectDay(day)}
>
	<time date-time={day.date}>{day.dayOfMonth}</time>
	<span className="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</button>
<button
	aria-disabled={day.isBooked ? 'true' : 'false'}
	aria-label={} // either the number or "already booked" or "selected"
	aria-selected={isDaySelected(day) ? 'true' : 'false'}
	className={...}
	onClick={() => selectDay(day)}
>
	<time date-time={day.date}>{day.dayOfMonth}</time>
	<span className="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</button>

This screenshot of the date picker with DevTools open shows how the individual date buttons are rendered on the site.

The Values of tabindex

tabindex="0" (Default value)

When a tabindex attribute is not specified for a focusable element, its default value is 0. This puts it in the Tab order of the page following the DOM source order.

The buttons in our date picker have some ARIA states and labels and an onClick but they do not specify tabindex. This means they have that default value of 0.

As in illustration, if we specify tabIndex="0" in our date button, the behavior will be the same as it was without specifying it at all.

Note: since we’re using React and JSX, our components use tabIndex in camelCase. The attribute name is not case sensitive in regular HTML.

<button
	aria-disabled={day.isBooked ? 'true' : 'false'}
	aria-label={} // either the number or "already booked" or "selected"
	aria-selected={isDaySelected(day) ? 'true' : 'false'}
	className={...}
	onClick={() => selectDay(day)}
	tabIndex="0"  // this is the default, so behavior won't change
>
<button
	aria-disabled={day.isBooked ? 'true' : 'false'}
	aria-label={} // either the number or "already booked" or "selected"
	aria-selected={isDaySelected(day) ? 'true' : 'false'}
	className={...}
	onClick={() => selectDay(day)}
	tabIndex="0"  // this is the default, so behavior won't change
>

tabindex="-1"

If we set the tabindex attribute on an element to -1, it will be taken out of the tab order and be unreachable with the Tab key.

Technically we can still use JavaScript to send focus to an element with a tabindex of -1, which is a piece of the puzzle in implementing roving tabindex.

The Roving Tabindex Plan of Attack

We want to be able to Tab onto a single day in the date picker, then use the Arrow keys to move around between the days. In doing this, we are creating a single tab stop for the entire control.

As we move around with the Arrow keys, we need to alter the tabindex attribute value for whatever button comes next in the desired direction. It will become focusable and all other days will be nonfocusable.

In this implementation, we will leverage React and JSX for the logic of tracking which buttons have a tabindex value of 0 and which have a tabindex of -1.
